Wash and dry all produce. Peel and mince @ginger{1%thumb}. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Trim, then thinly slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced, keeping greens and whites separate).

In a #large bowl{}, combine @shredded red cabbage{4%ounce}, @shredded carrots{4%ounce}, @white wine vinegar{2%tablespoon}, @sugar{1%tsp}, and a large pinch of @salt{}, tossing until thoroughly mixed. Set aside until rest of meal is ready.

> The longer slaw sits, the more flavorful it will be.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @ground pork{8%ounce}, ginger, garlic, scallion whites, @sesame oil{1%tsp}, and @soy sauce{1%tsp} (we'll be using the rest later). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Fill a #small bowl{} with @water{} and keep within reach.

Place a @wonton wrapper{1} on a dry, clean surface. Place 1 tsp filling in center of wrapper. Dip your fingers in water, then use them to moisten 2 adjacent edges of wrapper. Fold diagonally so that dry edges meet wet edges, forming a triangle. Press edges with fingers to seal. Set aside under a damp #paper towel{} and repeat until all filling is used.

Heat a thin layer of @vegetable oil{2%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add as many dumplings as can fit without crowding. Fry until crisp, about ~{1%minute} per side. Remove from pan and repeat with remainder. Return all dumplings to pan, arranging in an even layer. Reduce heat to low and pour in @water{1/4%cup}. Cover and let steam until wrappers are translucent, ~{4-6%minutes}. Uncover, increase heat to medium high, and evaporate water, about ~{2%minutes}.

While dumplings cook, whisk remaining @sesame oil{1%tablespoon}, remaining @soy sauce{1%tablespoon}, @sugar{1%TBSP}, and scallion greens in a small bowl until sugar dissolves. Divide dumplings between plates and serve with slaw on the side. Serve with sauce for dipping.